1.- Do the variable price requires transformation? Comment

Firstly, lets scatterplot price on surface to see what relation they potentally have:

plot( data$surface, data$price, xlab="Surface", ylab="Price")

We notice that there is a lot of dispersion of price the higher the house surface is. We will try to solve this by applying logarithms on the variable price:

data$lnprice = log(data$price)
plot(data$surface, data$lnprice,  xlab="Surface", ylab="lnPrice")

Looking at the graph, we can notice that the dispersion we had before changed to a more regular dispersion. So, we can conclude saying that the variable price requires a transformation: we compute the logarithm of this variable.

2.- Fit the linear regression of log(price) on the covariate surface

plot(data$surface, data$lnprice,  xlab="Surface", ylab="lnPrice")
model1 <- lm(lnprice~surface, data=data)
abline(model1, col="red")

As we saw on the previous section, doing the log of price, makes a model that is somewhat more ajusted than not doing logs but we have still a lot of dispersion.

3.- The same regression but for each of the groups defined by sold. The same two group regression but now with the same slop. Comment the results. Find a set of reasonable covariates for log(price) . Do a post fit analysis based on residuals vs fitted y plot, partial-regression plots, information on collinearity of predictor (for that you can use avPlots in the car Report on the multiple regression and extract general conclusions.

plot(data$surface[data$sold == 0], data$lnprice[data$sold == 0],  xlab="Surface", ylab="lnPrice", main="Unsold houses")
model2 <- lm(lnprice[sold == 0]~surface[sold == 0], data=data)
abline(model2, col="green", lty=2)
abline(model1, col="red")

plot(data$surface[data$sold == 1], data$lnprice[data$sold == 1],  xlab="Surface", ylab="lnPrice", main="Sold houses")
model2 <- lm(lnprice[sold == 1]~surface[sold == 1], data=data)
abline(model2, col="blue", lty=2)
abline(model1, col="red")

On red we have the regression line of the model without taking into account the sold variable. The green and blue regression lines are the regression lines of the model by splitting the variable sold. As we can see, the regression of not sold houses is quite similar to the regression of both groups together, the line is only a little bit shifted upwards. Looking at sold houses graph we see that is also a little bit shifted downwards but the slope is almost the same.

library(car)
## Loading required package: carData
model4 <- lm(lnprice ~ surface + sold + rural + pool + habSize + region, data=data)
avPlots(model4)

Now that we have this model, lets see residuals vs fitted values:

plot(model4$fitted.values, model4$residuals, xlab="Fitted values", ylab="Residuals")
abline(h=0, col="red")

4.- Now you are ask to find a predicting model for house prices. Which of the two models would you favor?: log(price) or log(price/surface)

The first model was done in the previous model. Lets see what adjusted r-squared we got on this model:

summary(model4)$r.squared
## [1] 0.5612799

Now lets compute the other model: log(price/surface)

lnpricesurface = log(data$price / data$surface)
model5 <- lm(lnpricesurface ~ sold + rural + pool + habSize + region, data=data)
summary(model5)$r.squared
## [1] 0.3874421

As we can see, we get a lower r-squared doing the log(price/surface). So we prefer the first model(lnprice)

5.- Using your final model, predict the selling prices of the unsold properties.

data2 <- subset(data, sold == 0)
predictedValues <- predict(model4, data2)
plot(predictedValues-data2$lnprice, ylab="Predicted Values - lnprice")

As we can see, our predicted values are quite good. The difference between the predicted value and the logarithm of the price are quite close to 0 on average for unsold properties.
